Independent of their habitat, chironomid larvae play an important role in the trophic chains of aquatic communities (
Schmid-Araya and Schmid 2000
). These organisms ingest various food items, such as algae and detritus and their associated microorganisms, besides some invertebrates (
Silva et al. 2008
). They also serve as food for many other aquatic invertebrates (
Schmid-Araya and Schmid 2000
). Among the several chironomid subfamilies, the 
Tanypodinae
larvae comprise the main predators in this family (
Merritt and Cummins 1984
).
